Hello,

While developing the scheduled lambda-function, I figured out that chalice doesn't delete the CloudWatch rules it has created during the deploy.

```
from chalice import Chalice
from chalice import Rate

app = Chalice(app_name='test')

@app.route('/')
def index():
    return {'hello': 'world'}

@app.schedule(Rate(1, unit=Rate.MINUTES))
def every_minute(event):
    print event.to_dict()

```
While deletion, Chalice deletes the REST API endpoint, lambda-function: test-dev, scheduled lambda-function: test-dev-every_minute and role: test-dev EXCEPT cloud watch rule: test-dev-every_minute

Kindly look into this.

When you want to check if a list contains an item you normally check by doing `.filter("list =", item)` but DatastoreInputReader validation is expecting a list instead of an item.

Should be
`mapper_params = {
            "filters": [("list", "=", item)]
        }`
instead of 
`mapper_params = {
            "filters": [("list", "=", [item])]
        }`

[Validate in source code](https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/appengine-mapreduce/blob/master/python/src/mapreduce/input_readers.py#L676)

The code [does the right thing](https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python/blob/13f8693d6bd135ec4a9e6289ce46f2e89bc185fc/gcloud/bigquery/table.py#L434) but the response from the server does not contain the necessary information.

The [docs](https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/docs/reference/v2/tables/insert) don't mention anything about this. I expect this comes from some `projection` default as with the GCS API but don't see anything in the docs.

@jgeewax Who can we ask about BigQuery API responses? (Maybe @fhoffa can say.)

The **streaming_recognize** method of **Sample** computes its output as follows:

```
        for response in responses:
            for result in response.results:
                if result.is_final or interim_results:
                    yield StreamingSpeechResult.from_pb(result)
```

Thus, it returns a generator where results are no longer grouped by response. I feel that this makes it more difficult for the end user to use the results, since results from the same response should be concatenated in order to obtain the complete transcript of the fragment transcribed so far.

@proppy 

Thought from working with this for the gcloud-python libraries; I'm wondering wondering if it makes sense to wrap each protobuf in an object to encapsulate methods in `helper` 

I'll add them to my fork and you can tell me what you think.

