This is a minor issue.

I recently observed the following from Z3's C API.

If I have a `Z3_func_decl` (e.g. `(declare x (_ BitVec 32))`) if I can convert this to a `Z3_ast` and request its sort Z3 will crash.

```c++
// Sketch of how to trigger crash
void test (Z3_func_decl fd, Z3_context ctx) {
  Z3_ast asAst = Z3_func_decl_to_ast(ctx, fd);
  Z3_sort sort = Z3_to_sort(ctx, asAst); // crashes
}
```

The issue appears to be that in the `get_sort(expr const * n)` function in `src/ast/ast.cpp` (around line 398) the switch case doesn't handle `AST_FUNC_DECL`.

In some ways this is probably to be expected because there are a separate set of APIs for getting the sorts for from a `Z3_func_decl` (i.e. `Z3_get_domain()` and `Z3_get_range()`). However it would be nice if Z3 handled the misuse of the API slightly more gracefully by calling the error handler. Alternatively it could just return what `Z3_get_range()` returns on the `Z3_func_decl` which is what I was initially expecting.

redux-observable [switched to using Epics over thunkservables](http://redux-observable.js.org/docs/FAQ.html#why-were-thunkservables-deprecated) a little while back. We've since added [fairly decent docs](http://redux-observable.js.org/docs/basics/Epics.html) on these but the tl;dr is that instead of dispatching a thunk that returns an observable, you dispatch regular POJO actions and listen for them in process managers called Epics which can then do your side effects in response and then they dispatch other actions when they're done with any response or signal.

I briefly looked through the nteract source and found two thunkservables as examples, [save/saveAs](https://github.com/nteract/nteract/blob/master/src/notebook/actions/index.js#L57).

They would be ported over to something _like_ this (untested...sorry!):

```js
// Extracted out for readability, but you don't have to or you can use
// something like the rxjs-fs package
const writeFileObservable = (filename, data, ...args) =>
  Observable.create(observer => {
    fs.writeFile(filename, data, ...args), error => {
      if (error) {
        observer.error(error);
      } else {
        observer.next({ filename, data });
        observer.complete();
      }
    });
  });

const SAVE = 'SAVE';
const SAVE_AS = 'SAVE_AS';

const save = (filename, notebook) => ({ type: SAVE: filename, notebook });
const saveAs = (filename, notebook) => ({ type: SAVE_AS: filename, notebook });

const saveEpic = actions =>
  actions.ofType(SAVE)
    .do(action => {
      // If there isn't a filename, save-as it instead
      if (!action.filename) {
        throw new Error('save needs a filename');
      }
    })
    .mergeMap(action =>
      writeFileObservable(filename, JSON.stringify(commutable.toJS(action.notebook), null, 1))
        .mapTo({ type: DONE_SAVING })
        // .startWith({ type: START_SAVING })
        // since SAVE effectively acts as the same as START_SAVING
        // you could just look for that in your reducers instead of START_SAVING
    );

const saveAsEpic = actions =>
  actions.ofType(SAVE_AS)
    .mergeMap(action => [
      { type: CHANGE_FILENAME, filename: action.filename },
      save(action.filename, action.notebook)
    ]);
```

